root.tree-val: Darling River Group, subtree of Pama-Nyungan: Wafer and Lissarrague 2008
root.pub-comments: "Hercus, however, notes that 'the unified name 'Paakantyi' has now become more and more prevalent among the people themselves for all of the 'River' groups' (1994: 41). This means that the term 'Paakantyi' (however it may be spelt) has, historically, two different usages. In the earlier usage, exemplified by Tindale, it may refer to a language vareity of the Darling River group--specifically the variety spoken roughly 'from Wilcannia downstream to nearly Avoca' (1974: 192). In the later usage, exemplified by Hercus, it may refer to the whole language that includes all varieties of the Darling River Group. Hercus attemps to avoid confusion over the references of the term by using 'Southern Paakantyi' to refer to 'the dialect once spoken from Avoca to Wilcannia' (1989: 48)" (Lissarrague and Wafer 2008: 263). Wafer and Lisserrague state that "Hercus has demonstrated in detail (1980, 1982, 1989, 1993, 1994) that the various distinct but closely related language varieties in this group… are dialects of a single language. She divides the "Darling River (Paakantyi) Language Group" into the 'nothern dialects' and the 'southern dialects'" (2008: 264).
root.publications: Lissarrague, Amanda & Jim Wafer. 2008. Handbook of Aboriginal Languages of New South Wales and the Australian Capital Territory. Nambucca Heads, NSW: Muurrbay Aboriginal Language and Culture Co-operative Ltd.ISBN 9780977535187
